assumptions:
  - "SQLite backfills existing sites rows to check_type=0 (:http) on add_column with default and null:false"
  - "Rails 8 integer-backed enums reject writes of out-of-range integers at the model layer (no raw 99 can be stored)"
  - "RSpec instance_double(Site, check_type: 'phantom') is a valid stand-in for the UnknownCheckType spec; it bypasses ActiveRecord's enum validation which would otherwise block a phantom type"

specifications:
  - "Site.check_type is an integer-backed enum with keys http/ssl/tcp/dns/content_match and default :http"
  - "CheckDispatcher.call(site) raises CheckDispatcher::UnknownCheckType for any check_type not explicitly routed — no silent fallback to HTTP"
  - "CheckDispatcher's public singleton surface is exactly .call; any additional public method is a structural-spec failure"
  - "CheckDispatcher exposes exactly one public constant: UnknownCheckType"
  - "UnknownCheckType bubbles out of PerformCheckJob#perform rather than being rescued into an error CheckResult, so Solid Queue's failed-job handling surfaces it operationally"
  - "Site.healthy? := up? (3-state meaning; Slice 9's :degraded is deliberately NOT healthy)"
  - "Site.failing? := down? (3-state meaning; Slice 9's :degraded is deliberately NOT failing)"
  - "before_validation :clear_irrelevant_config is wired on Site; the method body is intentionally empty in this slice and extended per-column by Slices 3-6 and 10"

deviations_from_plan: none

trade_offs: >
  Kept CheckDispatcher's public surface structurally pinned by a spec rather
  than only documented in a code comment. Cost: one extra spec file that turns
  red if the dispatcher ever grows a helper. Benefit: the dispatcher-discipline
  rule from the plan is enforced at CI time, not at code-review-discipline time,
  which is where drift always starts.

  Kept clear_irrelevant_config as an empty method + live callback rather than
  adding the callback lazily in Slice 3. Cost: one slice ships a no-op method
  with a single-line test that verifies wiring. Benefit: Slices 3-6 and 10 each
  add one field-scrubbing line without touching the callback-registration line,
  so the "add a column" diff stays small and obvious.

  UnknownCheckType is NOT rescued in PerformCheckJob. Cost: a bad deploy that
  ships a schema change without a matching dispatcher branch will fail loudly
  at job run time. Benefit: the failure is operationally visible (Solid Queue
  failed-job log) instead of silently recording ghost :down check results with
  a "CheckDispatcher has no route" error_message. Loud failure is the whole
  point of the exception class.

interfaces:
  consumed:
    - "HttpChecker.check(url) -> CheckOutcome"
  published:
    - "Site#check_type -> String"
    - "Site#check_type= (enum writer)"
    - "Site#http? -> Boolean (and the four sibling predicates)"
    - "Site#healthy? -> Boolean"
    - "Site#failing? -> Boolean"
    - "CheckDispatcher.call(site) -> CheckOutcome | raises CheckDispatcher::UnknownCheckType"
    - "CheckDispatcher::UnknownCheckType < StandardError"

self_review:
  tests: >
    Added spec/services/check_dispatcher_spec.rb with 6 examples: .call dispatches
    :http to HttpChecker, .call raises UnknownCheckType on phantom types, .call
    does not fall back to HttpChecker on phantom types, and three structural
    assertions pinning the public surface (one singleton method, one constant,
    no public instance methods). Extended spec/models/site_spec.rb with the
    check_type enum block (default, all five types, predicate sanity), the health
    predicate block (healthy? when up, failing? when down, neither when unknown),
    and a callback-wiring spec that pins the before_validation registration.
    Updated spec/jobs/perform_check_job_spec.rb to stub CheckDispatcher.call(site)
    instead of HttpChecker.check(site.url) at five stub sites.
  consistency: >
    CheckDispatcher.call(site) mirrors HttpChecker.check(url)'s singleton-method
    entrypoint pattern. The enum declaration syntax on Site matches the existing
    status enum line directly above it. The before_validation callback placement
    matches Rails convention (callbacks before validations in the class body).
  metz: >
    Measured. site.rb grew from 20 lines to 42 — 42 is under Metz's 100-line
    class limit. The new methods: healthy? 3 body lines, failing? 3 body lines,
    clear_irrelevant_config 2 body lines (1 is a comment placeholder, 1 blank
    — effectively an empty method body). check_dispatcher.rb is 23 lines total,
    1 public singleton method (call) at 6 body lines including the raise, 1
    nested exception class with a 3-line initialize. perform_check_job.rb
    perform unchanged shape (still 6 body lines).
  duplication: >
    HttpChecker.check(site.url) remains the only HTTP dispatch path; the job
    no longer calls it directly. No new copies of the enum values — the keys
    live in one place on Site.
  mocking: >
    check_dispatcher_spec uses instance_double(Site, ...) for the phantom-type
    case — owned internal code, instance_double verifies method existence so
    the test stays honest if Site's API changes. The :http happy-path test
    uses a real Site.create! and mocks HttpChecker.check (owned internal code).
    perform_check_job_spec mocks CheckDispatcher.call — owned internal code.
  error_paths: >
    UnknownCheckType is the one new error path this slice introduces. It is
    deliberately NOT rescued in PerformCheckJob#perform; the exception bubbles
    to Solid Queue's retry and failed-job handling. Two dispatcher specs pin
    this: one asserts the raise, one asserts HttpChecker is NOT called as a
    fallback. A third job spec assertion is deferred to a later slice where
    PerformCheckJob gets more rescue logic around :degraded — for Slice 2 the
    existing job specs all pass because they only exercise :http sites, which
    route cleanly.
  security: >
    No new security boundary touched. CheckDispatcher is a routing class with
    no user-data paths; Site.check_type writes go through ActiveRecord enum
    which rejects out-of-range writes at the model layer. Strong-params on
    sites_controller does not yet permit check_type (Slice 3 adds that with
    SSL); for Slice 2, sites can only be created/updated as :http through the
    UI, which is backward compatible with Epic 2.
  api: >
    Additive: Site#check_type, Site#check_type=, Site#healthy?, Site#failing?
    are all new; existing callers are unaffected. CheckDispatcher.call is a
    new published surface. PerformCheckJob's internal call site changed from
    HttpChecker.check to CheckDispatcher.call — not a public API change, all
    call-site specs updated in the same commit.
  dead_code: >
    clear_irrelevant_config has an empty body with a placeholder comment. Not
    dead code — the method exists as a deliberate callback seam for later
    slices, the wiring is tested, and the comment tells future readers why
    it looks empty. Removing it would force Slices 3-6 to add both the
    callback registration and the field-scrubbing line in the same diff,
    mixing two concerns.

